    "source": "convolute-B.md",
    "raw": "{\n\nmeta {\n  genre: \"material culture / temporal dialectics\"\n  convolute: \"B: Fashion\"\n  fragments: \"[B3a,4], [B4,6], [B4a,4], [B5,2], [B5a,2]\"\n  description: \"��We ~~We took the crinoline to be the symbol of the Second Empire in France-of its overblown lies, its hollow and purse-proud impudence. It toppled... . .\"\n}\n\nsource_text {\n  \"\"\"��We ~~We took the crinoline to be the symbol of the Second Empire in France-of its overblown lies, its hollow and purse-proud impudence. It toppled... . . just before the fall of the Empire, the Parisian world had time to indulge another another side of its temperament in women's fashions, and the Republic did not disdain to follow its lead.\\\" E E Th. Vischer, Mode und Cynismus (Stuttgart, 1879), p. 6.. The new fashion to which Vischer Vischer alludes is explained: ��The ~~The dress is cut diagonally across the hody and stretched over over... . . the helly\\\" (p. 6). A little later later he speaks of the women thus attired as �'naked ~'naked in their their clothes\\\" (p. 8). [B3a,S]\\n\\nFriedell explains, with regard to women, \\\"that the history of their their dress shows surprisingly few variatio\\n\\n---\\n\\nThe following remark makes it possible to recognize how fashion functions as camouflage for quite specifi specific interests of the ruling class. \\\"Rulers have a great aversion to violent changes. They want everything to stay the same-if possible, for a thousand years. If possible, the moon should stand still and the sun move no farther in in its course. Then no one would get hungry any more and want dinner. And when when the rulers have fired their shot, shot, the adversary should no longer be permitted to fire; fire; their own own shot should be the last.\\\" Bertolt Brecht, \\\"Fum Schwierigkeiten Schreiben der Wahrheit;' Unsere Schwierigkeiten beim Schreiben Zeit, 8, Basel, Prague, April 1935), p. p. 32. [B4a,l]\\n\\nMacOrlan, who emphasizes the analogies to Surrealism in Grandville's work, draws\\n\\n---\\n\\n. . like to frequent society and extract from its grand '''The creators of fashions... doings an impression of the whole; whole; they take part in its artistic life, are present at premieres and exhibitions, and read the hooks that make a sensation. In other words, they are inspired hy the... . . ferment... . . which the busy present day can offer. But since no present moment is ever fully cut off from the past, the latter also will offer attractions to the creator,... . . though only that which harmonizes with the reigning tone can be used. The toque tipped forward over the forehead, a style we owe to the Manet exhibition, demonstrates quite simply our new readiness to confront the end of of the previous century.\\\" Helen Grund, Yom Wesen del' Mode, p. 13. [B4a,S]\\n\\nOn the publicity war betw\\n\\n---\\n\\nA biological theory of of fashion that takes its cue from the evolution evolution of the zebra to the horse, as described in the abridged Brehm (p. 771):1l ��This ~~This evolution evolution spanned millions of years... ... The tendency in horses is toward the creation creation of a first-class runner and courser . . The most ancient of courser... . spicuously striped coats. Now, it is very remarkable that the external stripes ofthe zebra display a certain certain correspondence to the arrangement of the ribs and the vertebra inside. One can can also determine very clearly the arrangement of these parts from the unique striping on on the upper upper foreleg and upper upper hind leg. What do these stripes signify? A protective function can be ruled out,... . . The stripes have been . . prese\\n\\n---\\n\\n~~The ascendancy of the bourgeoisie works a change in women's wear. ��The hairstyles take on added dimensions... . . ; shoulders are enlarged by leg-of-mutton sleeves, and... . it was not long before the old hoop-petticoats came back into favor and full full skirts were the thing. Women, thus accoutered, appeared destined for a sedentary life-family life-since their manner of dress had about it nothing that could ever ever suggest or or seem to further the idea of movement. It was just the opposite with the advent of the Second Second Empire: Empire: family ties grew slack, and an ever-increasever-increasing luxury corrupted morals to such an extent that it became difficult to distin­ distinguish an honest woman from a courtesan on the basis of clothing alone. Feminine attire had thus been\"\"\"\n}\n\nlocations {\n  location <Convolute_B> {\n    description: \"Fashion\"\n    type: \"thematic_constellation\"\n  }\n}\n\nentities {\n  entity <Constellation_B_2> : textual_constellation {\n    traits: [Benjaminian, convolute_B, B3a_4_B4_6_B4a_4_B5_2_B5a_2]\n    location: <Convolute_B>\n  }\n}\n\nrelations {\n  rel [belongs_to](<Constellation_B_2> -> <Convolute_B>)\n}\n\nstates {\n  state <Convolute_B.status> = \"raw_material_for_dialectical_image\"\n}\n\ntimeline {\n  time <NineteenthCentury> {\n    description: \"The century of the arcades, the phantasmagoria, and the dream collective\"\n  }\n}\n\n}",
