    "raw": "{\n\nmeta {\n  genre: \"material culture / temporal dialectics\"\n  convolute: \"B: Fashion\"\n  fragments: \"[B7,8], [B7a,3], [B7a,4], [B9,3], [B9,4]\"\n  description: \"I:Il � ~ The following analysis of fashion incidentally throws a light on the significance of the trips that were fashionable among the bourgeoisie during the second half of r-rthe century. century.\"\n}\n\nsource_text {\n  \"\"\"I:Il � ~ The following analysis of fashion incidentally throws a light on the significance of the trips that were fashionable among the bourgeoisie during the second half of r-rthe century. century. \\\"The accent of attractions builds from their substantial center to their inception inception and their end. end. This This begins with with the most trifling symptoms, such as the... . switch switch from a cigar to a cigarette; cigarette; it is fully manifest in in the passion passion for traveling, which, with with its strong accentuations of departure and arrival, arrival, sets the life of the year vibrating as fully as possible in in several short periods. periods. The... . . tempo of modern life bespeaks not only the yearning for quick changes in in the qualitative content of life, but also\\n\\n---\\n\\nFuchs on Jhering's analysis of fashion: fashion: \\\"It must... . be reiterated that the concern for segregating the classes is only one cause of the frequent variation in fashions, and that a second cause-the private-capitalist mode of production, which in the interests of its profit margin must continually multiply the possibilities of turn­ turnover-is of equal importance. This cause has escaped Jhering entirely, as has a third: the function of erotic stimulation in fashion, which operates most effectively when the erotic attractions of the man or the woman appear in ever new settings... ... Friedrich Vischer, who wrote about fashion... .. twenty years before Jhering, did not yet recognize, in the genesis of fashion, the tendencies at work to keep the classes divided;... . on the other oth\\n\\n---\\n\\nEduard Fuchs (Illustrierte Sittengeschichte vom Mittelalter bis zur Gegenwart: Das biirgerliche Zeitalter, enlarged ed., pp. 56-57) cites-without references-a remark by F.F. Th. Vischer, according to which the gray of men's clothing symbolsymbolizes the \\\"utterly blast?' character character of the masculine world, its dullness and inertia. [BS,!]\\n\\n��One ~~One of the surest and most deplorable symptoms of that weakness and frivolity of character which marked the Romantic age was the childish and fatal notion of rejecting the deepest understanding of technical procedures,... . . the consciously sustained and orderly orderly carrying through of a work... .. -all for the sake of the spontaneous impulses of the individual sensibility. The idea of creating works of lasting value lost force and ga\\n\\n---\\n\\n]\\n\\nLipps on the somber cast of men ''8 clothing: clothing: He thinks that �'our ~'our general aversion to bright colors, bright colors, especially especially in in clothing for men, clothing for men, evinces evinces very very clearly clearly an an oft-noted peculiarity of our character. Gray is all all theory; green-and not only green but also red, yellow, blue-is the golden tree of life. 222 In our predilection for the various shades of gray... . . running to black, we find an unmistakable social reflection of our tendency our tendency to to privilege privilege the the theory of the theory of the formation formation of of intellect intellect above above all all else. Even the beautiful we can no longer just enjoy; rather,... . . we must first subject it to criticism, with the consequence \\n\\n---\\n\\nFashions are a collective medicament for the ravages of oblivion. The more shortshortlived a period, the more susceptible it is to fashion. fashion. Compare K2a,3. [B9a,I]\\n\\nFocillon on the phantasmagoria of fashion: fashion: \\\"Most often... . . it creates hybrids; hybrids; it imposes on the human being the profi profile of an animal... ... Fashion thus invents an artificial humanity which is not the passive decoration of a formal environment, but that very environment itself. Such a humanity-by turns heraldic, theatrical, fantastical, architectural-takes, as its ruling principle, the poetics of ornament, and what it calls 'line'... . . is perhaps hut a subtle compromise between a certain physiological canon... . . and imaginative design.\\\" Henri Focillon, Vie des formes (Paris, 1934), p. 41.\"\"\"\n}\n\nlocations {\n  location <Convolute_B> {\n    description: \"Fashion\"\n    type: \"thematic_constellation\"\n  }\n}\n\nentities {\n  entity <Constellation_B_3> : textual_constellation {\n    traits: [Benjaminian, convolute_B, B7_8_B7a_3_B7a_4_B9_3_B9_4]\n    location: <Convolute_B>\n  }\n}\n\nrelations {\n  rel [belongs_to](<Constellation_B_3> -> <Convolute_B>)\n}\n\nstates {\n  state <Convolute_B.status> = \"raw_material_for_dialectical_image\"\n}\n\ntimeline {\n  time <NineteenthCentury> {\n    description: \"The century of the arcades, the phantasmagoria, and the dream collective\"\n  }\n}\n\n}",
