    "raw": "{\n\nmeta {\n  genre: \"urban politics / revolutionary topology\"\n  convolute: \"E: Haussmannization, Barricade Fighting\"\n  fragments: \"[E3a,2], [E3a,4], [E4a,1], [E4a,4], [E5a,4]\"\n  description: \"''New arteries... . . would link the center of Paris with the railroad stations, reducreducing congestion in the latter. latter.\"\n}\n\nsource_text {\n  \"\"\"\\\"'New arteries... . . would link the center of Paris with the railroad stations, reducreducing congestion in the latter. latter. Others would take part in the battle against poverty and revolution; they would be strategic routes, breaking through the sourees of contagion and the centers of unrest, and permitting, with the influx of better air, the arrival of an armed force, hence connecting, like the Rue de Turbigo, the government with the barracks barracks~� and, like the Boulevard du Prince-Eugfme, the barracks with the suburbs.\\\" Georges Laronze, Le Baron Haussmann, pp. 137- 1371�. 1~. ~a~]\\n\\n\\\"An independent deputy, the comte de Durfort-Civrac,... .. objected that these new boulevards, which were supposed to aid in repressing disturbances, would order to construct them, it was necessary a\\n\\n---\\n\\nHaussmann celebrates the birthday-or name day (April 5)'I-of Napoleon III. \\\"Running the length of the Champs-Elysees, from the Place de la Conconle to the Etoile, there was a scalloped border of 124 sculpted arcades reposing on a double row of columns. 'It is a reminiscence reminiscence~' � ' Le Constitutionnel sought to explain~� \\\"of Cordova and the Alhambra.'... . . The visual effect was thus very striking, with t.he swirling branches of the fifty-six great streetlights along the avenue avenue~� the reflections from the surfaces below, and the flickering of flames from the five hundred thou119. Flaneur 0 gas.\\\" Georges Laronze, Le Baron Haltssmann, p. 119.0 sand jets of gas [E3a,S]\\n\\nOn Haussmann: Haussmann: \\\"Paris now ceased forever to be a conglomeration of small towns, each with its dis\\n\\n---\\n\\nFerry analyzes (pp. 21-23 of his ComptesJantastiques) the judgments judgments rendered in cases of expropriation-judgments which, in the course of Haussmann's projects, took on a tendency unfavorable to the city. Following a decree of December December 27, 1858--which Ferry regards as merely the normalization of an ancient right, but which Haussmann regards as the establishment of a new right-the city was de­ denied the possibility of expropriating in t..heir heir entirety properties which lay in the way of the new arteries. The expropriation was limited to those portions immediimmediately required for the construction of the streets. In this way, the city lost out on the profits it had hoped to make from the sale of remaining plots of land, whose value was driven up by the construction. [\\n\\n---\\n\\nAround 1830: ��The ~~The Rue Saint-Denis and Rue Saint-Martin are the principal ar­ arteries in this quartier, a godsend for rioters. The war for the streets was deplorably easy there. The rebels had only to rip up the pavement and then pile up various objects: furniture from neighboring houses, crates from the grocer's, and, if need be, a passing omnibus, which they would stop, gallantly helping the ladies to disembark. In order to gain these Thermopylaes, it was thus necessary to demolish the houses. The line infantry would advance into the open, heavily armed and well equipped. A handful of of insurgents behind a barricade could hold an entire regiregiment at bay,\\\" Dubech and d'Espezel, Histoire de Paris (Paris, 1926), pp. 365-366. [E4a,S]\\n\\nUnder Louis Philippe: r.�In r.~In the interior\\n\\n---\\n\\n.r.Until Haussmann, Paris had been a city of moderate dimensions, where it was I.r.Until logical to let experience rule; it developed according to pressures dictated by na­nature, according to laws inscribed in the facts of history and in the face of the landscape. Brusquely, Haussmann accelerates and crowns the work of revolutionrevolutionary and imperial centralization... . An artificial and inordinate creation, emerged like Minerva from the head of Jupiter, born amid the abuse of the spirit of authority, this work had need of the spirit of authority in order order to develop accordaccording to its own logic. No sooner sooner was it born, than it was cut off at the source... ... . Here was the paradoxical spectacle of a construction artifiartificial in principle but abandoned in fact onl\"\"\"\n}\n\nlocations {\n  location <Convolute_E> {\n    description: \"Haussmannization, Barricade Fighting\"\n    type: \"thematic_constellation\"\n  }\n}\n\nentities {\n  entity <Constellation_E_2> : textual_constellation {\n    traits: [Benjaminian, convolute_E, E3a_2_E3a_4_E4a_1_E4a_4_E5a_4]\n    location: <Convolute_E>\n  }\n}\n\nrelations {\n  rel [belongs_to](<Constellation_E_2> -> <Convolute_E>)\n}\n\nstates {\n  state <Convolute_E.status> = \"raw_material_for_dialectical_image\"\n}\n\ntimeline {\n  time <NineteenthCentury> {\n    description: \"The century of the arcades, the phantasmagoria, and the dream collective\"\n  }\n}\n\n}",
